### Visual Reference: Consistency, Contradiction, Contrary

#### 🔵 Table D — Relations between TWO sentences A and B

For any two sentences, exactly one of these relations holds:

| Relation | Can both be TRUE? | Can both be FALSE? | Memorable Example |
|----------|:-----------------:|:------------------:|-------------------|
| **Contradictory** | ❌ No | ❌ No | "It is raining" / "It is NOT raining" |
| **Contrary** (mutually exclusive) | ❌ No | ✅ Yes | "Trump is happy" / "Trump is unhappy" (both false if neutral) |
| **Consistent** (compatible) | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | "Trump is happy" / "Trump is American" |
| **Subcontrary** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | "Some birds fly" / "Some birds don't fly" |

> **⚠️ Common trap:** "Trump is happy" and "Trump is unhappy" are **CONTRARIES**, not contradictories — because both can be false (if Trump is neither happy nor unhappy). This is why T/F question #10 in the outline is **False**.
>
> The true contradictory of "Trump is happy" is "Trump is NOT happy" (the outright negation).

#### 🟣 Table E — Truth Table for Contradictories

If A and B are contradictory, the possible combinations are:

| A | B | Possible? |
|:-:|:-:|:---------:|
| T | T | ❌ No |
| T | F | ✅ Yes |
| F | T | ✅ Yes |
| F | F | ❌ No |

> Contradictories always have **opposite** truth values, in every possible situation.

---

### Visual Reference: Consistency of Sets

#### 🟡 Table F — Consistent vs. Inconsistent Sets

| Set Γ | Is it Consistent? | Reason |
|-------|:-----------------:|--------|
| {"Snow is white", "Grass is green"} | ✅ Consistent | Both can be true together |
| {"Snow is white", "Grass is red"} | ✅ Consistent | *Possible* that both are true, even if one is false |
| {"Snow is white", "Snow is NOT white"} | ❌ Inconsistent | Contradictory pair — can't both be true |
| {"All birds fly", "Penguins are birds", "Penguins don't fly"} | ❌ Inconsistent | No contradictories, but jointly impossible |

> **Consistency is about *possibility*, not about actual truth.** A set can be consistent even if some members are actually false, as long as they *could have been* jointly true.

#### 🧠 Key Relationship: Consistency ↔ Validity

| Statement | True? |
|-----------|:-----:|
| If premises are inconsistent, the argument is automatically valid. | ✅ TRUE |
| In a valid argument, premises + **negation of conclusion** form an **inconsistent** set. | ✅ TRUE |
| In an invalid argument, premises + negation of conclusion form a **consistent** set. | ✅ TRUE |

> This gives you a **test for validity**: negate the conclusion and check whether the resulting set is inconsistent. If yes → valid. If no → invalid.

