## Meditation Three — The Existence of God (Trademark Argument)

### Setup: Clear and Distinct Rule (tentative)

> "Whatever I perceive very clearly and distinctly is true."

This is proposed as a general rule *based on* the certainty of the cogito — but it is *provisional* until God's existence and veracity are established.

### Classification of Thoughts
- **Ideas (images proper):** as it were pictures of things.
- **Volitions & emotions:** involve willing or feeling toward something.
- **Judgments:** involve affirmation/denial — only here can truth or falsity strictly arise.

**Broader sense of "idea":** the form of any thought, the immediate perception of which makes me aware of the thought. (Hence we have ideas of even numbers, though no image of them.)

### Bearers of Falsity
- **Formal falsity** belongs to judgments — affirming what is not the case.
- **Material falsity** belongs to ideas — an idea is materially false if it is obscure or confused and provides occasion for erroneous judgment (e.g., the idea of cold as a positive quality when it is really just a privation of heat).

### Three Kinds of Ideas (by origin)
1. **Innate** — born with us (e.g., idea of God, of self, of mathematical truths).
2. **Adventitious** — come from outside (e.g., hearing a sound, seeing the sun).
3. **Invented (factitious)** — produced by myself (e.g., sirens, hippogriffs).

### Two Grades of Belief
- **Spontaneous impulse (natural inclination)** — not always reliable; can mislead.
- **Natural light (lumen naturale)** — absolutely reliable; reveals self-evident truths (e.g., "nothing comes from nothing").

### Formal vs. Objective Reality — The Crucial Distinction
This is one of Descartes' most important technical moves.

- **Formal (actual) reality:** The reality a thing has in virtue of actually existing. A substance has more formal reality than a mode; infinite substance (God) has the most.
- **Objective reality:** The reality something possesses *insofar as it is represented by an idea*. It is the representational content of the idea.

**Hierarchy of Reality:**
```
God (infinite substance)       — highest formal reality
   │
Created substances (minds, bodies) — medium formal reality
   │
Modes of substance              — lowest formal reality
```
Ideas mirror this hierarchy in their *objective* content: the idea of God contains more objective reality than the idea of a substance, which contains more than the idea of a mode.

### The Causal Principles

**Metaphysical Causal Principle (MCP):**
> There must be at least as much reality in the efficient and total cause as in the effect.

**Causal Principle for Objective Reality (CPOR):**
> The cause of the objective reality of an idea must contain formally (or eminently) at least as much reality as the idea contains objectively.

**Formal containment:** the cause contains the feature in the same manner as the effect.
**Eminent containment:** the cause contains the feature in a higher, more perfect manner.

### The Trademark Argument for God's Existence

1. Nothing comes from nothing. *(Natural light)*
2. Everything has a cause. *(From 1)*
3. CPOR: For any idea with objective reality R, its cause must contain formally or eminently at least R reality. *(Natural light)*
4. I have an idea of God — infinite, eternal, omniscient, omnipotent, all-perfect substance. *(Empirical premise)*
5. My idea of God has a cause. *(From 2, 4)*
6. The idea of God contains the highest level of objective reality. *(Definition of "God" + hierarchy)*
7. So the cause of my idea of God must contain the highest level of formal reality. *(From 3, 5, 6)*
8. Only God contains the highest level of formal reality. *(Definition of "God")*
9. Therefore, the cause of my idea of God is God Himself. *(From 7, 8)*
10. **Therefore, God exists.** *(From 5, 9)*

**Called "trademark" argument** because the idea of God in me is like the artisan's mark stamped on his work.

### Why the Idea of God Is Not Derived From Anywhere Else
- **Not from negation of the finite** — the positive idea of infinity is prior to the idea of the finite (I recognize my finitude only by contrast with the infinite).
- **Not materially false** — the idea is utterly clear and distinct.
- **Not from me as a potentially perfect being** — a merely potential perfection cannot produce an actual one (potency cannot cause actuality at a higher level).

### The Second Proof — From My Own Existence
From whom do I derive my existence? Four options:

- **(i) From myself** — then I should be God (self-sufficient, all-perfect). Absurd, since I clearly lack perfections.
- **(ii) From nothing / eternally self-sustaining** — I should be immediately aware of a power to preserve my own existence. I have no such awareness.
- **(iii) From parents or causes less perfect than God** — but my existence requires preservation each moment (concurrence). Tracing back causes cannot be an infinite regress; must terminate in God.
- **(iv) From several partial causes** — but the inseparability of divine attributes (simplicity) is itself a divine attribute. So perfection cannot come piecemeal.

**Conclusion:** I derive my existence from God. Therefore, God exists.

### Consequences
- The idea of God is **innate** (not adventitious, not invented).
- **God is not a deceiver.** Deception is a defect; the most perfect being has no defects.

### Objections & Replies Highlights
- **"All ideas are adventitious"** — Descartes denies; some (like God, self, mathematical truths) bear the mark of innateness.
- **"We have no idea of God, only a word"** — Descartes: we *do* have a clear and distinct idea, even if not fully adequate (we understand, we don't fully comprehend).
- **"The human intellect can't conceive infinity"** — understanding ≠ fully adequate conception. We grasp infinity imperfectly, yet clearly.
- **"The idea of infinity is constructed by successive degrees"** — Descartes: successive addition gives only the *indefinite*, not the *infinite*. They differ in kind.
- **"Objective reality is not real, needs no cause"** — Descartes: objective reality is a genuine mode of being (of representation), less perfect than formal but not nothing.
- **Difference from Aquinas' Five Ways:** Aquinas argues from empirical features of the world; Descartes argues from the content of a single idea within the thinker. Descartes' argument is purely *a priori*.

